Removing seasonality?

Seasonality inflates correlation estimates:

set.seed(123)

# Generate data
n <- 120
time <- 1:n

seasonality1 <- sin(2 * pi * time / 24) + cos(2 * pi * time / 24)
seasonality2 <- 0.8 * sin(2 * pi * time / 24 + pi / 4) + 0.5 * cos(2 * pi * time / 24)

noise1 <- rnorm(n, mean = 0, sd = 0.5)
noise2 <- rnorm(n, mean = 0, sd = 0.5)

var1 <- seasonality1 + noise1
var2 <- seasonality2 + noise2
data <- data.frame(time = time, var1 = var1, var2 = var2)

# Remove seasonality using regression
data$var1_detrended <- lm(var1 ~ sin(2 * pi * time / 24) + cos(2 * pi * time / 24), data = data)$residuals
data$var2_detrended <- lm(var2 ~ sin(2 * pi * time / 24) + cos(2 * pi * time / 24), data = data)$residuals

plot1 <- ggplot(data, aes(x = time)) +
  geom_line(aes(y = var1, color = "Variable 1")) +
  geom_line(aes(y = var2, color = "Variable 2")) +
  labs(title = "Variables with Less Frequent Seasonality", y = "Value", color = "Variable") +
  theme_minimal()

plot2 <- ggplot(data, aes(x = time)) +
  geom_line(aes(y = var1_detrended, color = "Variable 1")) +
  geom_line(aes(y = var2_detrended, color = "Variable 2")) +
  labs(title = "Variables without Seasonality (Detrended)", y = "Value", color = "Variable") +
  theme_minimal()

print(plot1)

print(plot2)

There are different ways to approach this:

  1. Decompose Seasonality for Each City/Port Separately
  2. Compute an Aggregated Seasonal Trend Across All Countries

Let’s do both and see the result. Just a single city as an example:

# Combine year and month into a Date column
data <- city_df[city_df$city_id == "26553", c("year","month","light")] %>%
  mutate(date = as.Date(paste(year, month, "01", sep = "-")))

# Apply STL  to remove seasonality (for a single city/port in this case)
ts_data <- ts(data$light, frequency = 12)  
decomposed <- stl(ts_data, s.window = "periodic")

# Extract the components (trend, seasonal, residuals)
trend     <- decomposed$time.series[, "trend"]
seasonal  <- decomposed$time.series[, "seasonal"]
residuals <- decomposed$time.series[, "remainder"]

data <- data %>%
  mutate(trend = trend,
         seasonal = seasonal,
         residuals = residuals)

ggplot(data) +
  geom_line(aes(x = date, y = light, color = "Raw Data", linetype = "Solid"), size = 1) +
  geom_line(aes(x = date, y = trend, color = "Trend", linetype = "Dashed"), size = 1) +
  geom_line(aes(x = date, y = seasonal, color = "Season", linetype = "Dashed"), size = 1) +
  geom_line(aes(x = date, y = residuals, color = "Detrended+Deseasoned", linetype = "Solid"), size = 1) +
  labs(
    title = paste("Light Intensity Decomposition: City", 26553),
    x = "Date",
    y = "Light Intensity") +
  theme_minimal() +

Another extreme: computing overall season across all cities/ports in all countries

# Combine year and month into a Date column
data <- city_df[, c("city_id","year","month","light")] %>%
  mutate(date = as.Date(paste(year, month, "01", sep = "-")))

# Aggregate light intensity by month across all cities/ports
aggregated_seasonal <- data %>%
  group_by(month) %>%
  summarize(avg_light = mean(light, na.rm = TRUE))

# Join the aggregated seasonal pattern back to the original data

  left_join(aggregated_seasonal, by = "month") %>%

Summarizing Light Intensity

One commonly used measure is the ratio of seasonal variance to total variance, which captures how much of the variability in light intensity is explained by seasonal fluctuations.

  1. Decompose the Time Series: Decompose the monthly light intensity into trend, seasonal, and residual components using a method like STL (Seasonal-Trend decomposition using Loess).

  2. Calculate Seasonal Strength: Compute the seasonal strength as:

\[S = 1 - \frac{\text{Var(Residuals)}}{\text{Var(Original Series)}}\]This value will be between 0 and 1, where values closer to 1 indicate stronger seasonality.

# Calculate average light intensity by year, month, and distance bin
country_light <- data %>%
  group_by(name, year, month) %>%
  summarise(avg_light = mean(light, na.rm = TRUE), .groups = 'drop')

# Step 1: Define function to calculate seasonality strength
calculate_seasonality_strength <- function(light_intensity) {
  ts_data <- ts(light_intensity, frequency = 12)  # Monthly data (12 periods per year)
  decomposition <- stl(ts_data, s.window = "periodic")  # STL decomposition
  seasonal_var <- var(decomposition$time.series[, "seasonal"], na.rm = TRUE)
  total_var <- var(light_intensity, na.rm = TRUE)
  strength <- seasonal_var / total_var
  return(strength)
}

# Step 2: Apply the function to each country
seasonality_summary <- country_light %>%
  group_by(name) %>%
  summarise(seasonality_strength = calculate_seasonality_strength(avg_light)) %>%
  ungroup()

# Step 3: Merge seasonality data with spatial data
africa <- africa  %>%
  left_join(seasonality_summary, by = c("sovereignt" = "name"))

# Step 4: Plot the map
ggplot(africa) +
  geom_sf(aes(fill = seasonality_strength)) +
  scale_fill_viridis_c(option = "magma", na.value = "grey90", name = "Seasonality Strength") +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(
    title = "Seasonality Strength Across Countries",
    subtitle = "Based on Average Monthly Light Intensity",
    caption = "Source: country_light data"
  ) +
  theme(
    legend.position = "right",
    panel.grid = element_blank()
  )
